04357nmm a2200721Ia 9781479878680DE-B159720240326120151.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240326t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97814798786807 a10.18574/nyu/9781479861958.001.00012doi  a(DE-B1597)547003  a(OCoLC)912234332  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aPN1995.9.P795bP86 2016 7aLAW0260002bisacsh04a791.436556223  aAP 19830qSEPA2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/7057:202100aPunishment in Popular Culture /ced. by Austin Sarat, Charles J. Ogletree Jr. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Charles Hamilton Houston Institute Series on Race and Justice ;v40 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe way a society punishes demonstrates its commitment to standards of judgment and justice, its distinctive views of blame and responsibility, and its particular way of responding to evil. Punishment in Popular Culture examines the cultural presuppositions that undergird America’s distinctive approach to punishment and analyzes punishment as a set of images, a spectacle of condemnation. It recognizes that the semiotics of punishment is all around us, not just in the architecture of the prison, or the speech made by a judge as she sends someone to the penal colony, but in both “high” and “popular” culture iconography, in novels, television, and film. This book brings together distinguished scholars of punishment and experts in media studies in an unusual juxtaposition of disciplines and perspectives.Americans continue to lock up more people for longer periods of time than most other nations, to use the death penalty, and to racialize punishment in remarkable ways. How are these facts of American penal life reflected in the portraits of punishment that Americans regularly encounter on television and in film? What are the conventions of genre which help to familiarize those portraits and connect them to broader political and cultural themes? Do television and film help to undermine punishment's moral claims? And how are developments in the boarder political economy reflected in the ways punishment appears in mass culture? Finally, how are images of punishment received by their audiences? It is to these questions that Punishment in Popular Culture is addressed.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aMass media and criminal justicexUnited StatesxUnited States. 0aMass media and criminal justicezUnited States. 0aMotion picturesxHistoryxUnited States. 0aMotion pictureszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aPunishment in motion pictures. 0aPunishment in popular culturezUnited States. 0aPunishment on television. 0aTelevision broadcastingxUnited States. 0aTelevision broadcastingzUnited States. 7aLAW / Criminal Law / General.2bisacsh1 aOgletree Jr., Charles J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aSarat, Austin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479861958.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479878680423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479878680/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles